{"id":"2208.05425","submitter":"Suhyeon Lee","authors":"Suhyeon Lee, Donghwan Lee, and Seungjoo Kim","title":"Block Double-Submission Attack: Block Withholding Can Be\n  Self-Destructive","comments":"This paper is an extended version of a paper accepted to ACM Advances\n  in Financial Techologies - AFT 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  Proof-of-Work (PoW) is a Sybil control mechanism adopted in blockchain-based\ncryptocurrencies. It prevents the attempt of malicious actors to manipulate\ndistributed ledgers. Bitcoin has successfully suppressed double-spending by\naccepting the longest PoW chain. Nevertheless, PoW encountered several major\nsecurity issues surrounding mining competition. One of them is a Block\nWithHolding (BWH) attack that can exploit a widespread and cooperative\nenvironment called a mining pool. This attack takes advantage of untrustworthy\nrelationships between mining pools and participating agents. Moreover,\ndetecting or responding to attacks is challenging due to the nature of mining\npools. In this paper, however, we suggest that BWH attacks also have a\ncomparable trust problem. Because a BWH attacker cannot have complete control\nover BWH agents, they can betray the belonging mining pool and seek further\nbenefits by trading with victims. We prove that this betrayal is not only valid\nin all attack parameters but also provides double benefits; finally, it is the\nbest strategy for BWH agents. Furthermore, our study implies that BWH attacks\nmay encounter self-destruction of their own revenue, contrary to their\nintention.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Aug 2022 16:17:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 30 Aug 2022 12:14:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-31"}
