\nalgorithm providers are bound to perform under current regulatory frameworks.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 Aug 2022 09:40:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-15"}
{"id":"2208.06245","submitter":"Bo Li","authors":"Bo Li and Chi Ho Yeung","title":"Understanding the stochastic dynamics of sequential decision-making\n  processes: A path-integral analysis of Multi-armed Bandits","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LG cond-mat.dis-nn physics.soc-ph stat.ML","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The multi-armed bandit (MAB) model is one of the most classical models to\nstudy decision-making in an uncertain environment. In this model, a player\nneeds to choose one of K possible arms of a bandit machine to play at each time\nstep, where the corresponding arm returns a random reward to the player,\npotentially from a specific unknown distribution. The target of the player is\nto collect as much rewards as possible during the process. Despite its\nsimplicity, the MAB model offers an excellent playground for studying the\ntrade-off between exploration versus exploitation and designing effective\nalgorithms for sequential decision-making under uncertainty. Although many\nasymptotically optimal algorithms have been established, the finite-time\nbehaviours of the stochastic dynamics of the MAB model appears much more\ndifficult to analyze, due to the intertwining between the decision-making and\nthe rewards being collected. In this paper, we employ techniques in statistical\nphysics to analyze the MAB model, which facilitates to characterize the\ndistribution of cumulative regrets at a finite short time, the central quantity\nof interest in an MAB algorithm, as well as the intricate dynamical behaviours\nof the model.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 Aug 2022 09:32:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-15"}
